{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_cotton_ver04/data/sn91068761/00279559174/1958040201/1048.xml":{"full_text":"Carter's\nColumn\nIi\u00bb\u2014-W. Horace Carter\nRUNNING: We don't know whether Al VVillian will offici\nally uur.c.unce his candidacy for Recorders Court Judge before\nthis weeks paper gets out or not but anyhow he*.\u00b7 running. The\nformer Tabor City mayor is one of the best known political fig\nures in '.'\u03c7\u00b7 county, and we expect him to make \u03c1 mighty good\nrun for \"he judge's post. Ai is one of the roil ta\u00bbk<r.g-type poli\nticians who can make friends quickly and get \\o too. Hi lo>t\nin his i.-ci- for State senior a few years ago but onlv by a hand\nful of >.oVs. We 1\" k I m be in the very tlrck <-f the race\nfor jinit;\u00b7 i race.\nl iiei ''s one ti.ing about lum. he is iu\\cr at a I\u00b7 i\u00b7\" wor\nand a; nuets no sli; tigers. Everyone is a friend it he gets a\nchan. talk.\ndAIX: Many u Iks say tiie water that fell \u039b\u039a-ti ia\\ trorning\nbei'\u00b7\u00bb .\u03b9 was tl. most that has fell at all during ti e eiu.ie wet\nwinter. 'J hat woul i certainly be a lot of rainfall o.it 't ma\\ have\nbeen \"h.\u00b7 most. Yards and fields were flooded throitf out a wide\narea.\nMIL.3-.POND: Time's about here for anjtlier l ake Tabor\nstocKhokVis meeting. It brmgs to mind the need !or adequate\nfunds ivy improve t. at tine project. It also buries to mind the need\nfor uii\u00bb>\u03b9, will: winch maintain the present project. l!ut this\nis the yji that lis: n- should improve at Lake Tabor and if the\nfish bio.\u00b7 well enu. gh, iere'11 be revenue. This is a fishing\ncountry.\ncn~>ui\u00b7 e \u03bd\u03af.. iiat; .aiiu wiuic we are taming uOvlit projects,\nthe vlub house >1111 awaits some work bet\u00f6re the ounny club\ncan 4. ili UoiHalt' a diucn times the director; have set ten\ntative opening d^ttes for beginning golt play but the unpredictable\nweather as stalled e\\ery thing. It we can just have two 01 three\nweeks good, spnnfc. weather with a minimum rainfall. the\ngulf \u00bbJUi. e will be in business.\nM&RCHANTS: Every member of the Board of Directors of\nthe Tab\u00bb: City Merchants Association was present \"ten commit\ntee appointment were made Monday morning. Tune's a great\ndeal \u03b7 'trerest in fcoing places with the association this year and\nlengtln discussions took place on farm diversification, the pro\nposal hjspital, tlie need tor doctors, town-wide promotions, credit\nbureau ut.d a variety of other things. It is a health.\u00b7 situation to\nsee businessmen concerned over the economic situation and anxi\nous to Co everything possible about it.\nRE^iSSION: We are the first to admit that we don't know\nanyth'ng about anything. But there are several .nchcations that\nthe so-called recession may either be on the way ip or at least\nstalljd toi awhile. Bank deposits last quarter were way up. Un\nemplo.\u00bb :r..*nt the country over is widespread but powers that be\nthink tltui is now on the decrease. All this may \u03b7 t help the\nplight oi the tobacco fai r- r but we would like to see some one\ndoing all right even if ne do have to struggle. And after awhile,\nif the iest of the land prospers, we will too. We'1) eventually\ndiversity and industralize.\nROTARY: Several folks have asked why we h:i\\ ent's earned\na story aiiout the Rotary Club eleetion at which tim we got nam\ned p-e^if.cnt lor the new year, bciiinnin^ July 1. Tit\" truth is, the\nelection came on the same week that Grovcr Md'herson and I\ngot the dubious distinction ot beinj* named County Red Cross\nco-chairni\u00bbn for t'.e annual :und drive. It looked like little ti>o\nmuch \u03bf\u03af a gi\u00bbod thing to announce that and tiie ftot.rv election\nat th same time. Anyhow, having served as vi-.v-prcsiilent or\nfour or \"iu years. Reparians kind of figured it was time to net\nme )ut that position c.nti kicked me upstairs. L t I don't want\nto mm :\u03c4\u03b9. e the Rotary presidency. It's a real hon\u00ab.\u00b7\u00b7' to serve that\nclub as president. It's the old original civic tlub in Tabor City\nand alt:;' ugh there are time.\u00b7 vhen folks wond-\u00b7\u00b7 just what it\ndoes. i. has served many yea:\u00b7- quietly yet wi:'i noteworthy\nachievement. We're proud of the Tabor City Rotary \"lub and the\nPrivileg\u00b7\u00b7 of being among its m :nbersh:p.\nI\u2014\"\u2014\u2014\u2014\nEditorials\nLAST CALL FOR SEALS\nApproach of the joyous Easter sea\nson may result in many persons over\nlooking the fact that all humans do\nnot have the ordinary everyday\npleasures of life, such as walking.\nIt is the crippled children that the\nNorth Carolina Society for Crippled\nChildren hopes to help each year by\nraising funds to give as many as pos\nsible relief from the torture of being\nphysically handicapped.\nRight now the Society is in the\nmidst of its drive to raise funds for\ncrippled youngsters through the sale\nof Laster seals. There's no maximum\nyou can pay for lite sheets of seals\nthat have been sent you. The bigger\nthe contribution the more it will be\nappreciated. However, if you can't\ngive a big sum, give what you can.\nAny amount will be appreciated.\nWhile the drive primarily is an ap\npeal to relieve suffering among chil\ndren it also covers relief among\nadults. t\nEvery possible means of relieving\ncrippling conditions among children\nand adults are resorted to by the\nSociety. However, the extent of tbe\nrelief depends upon the individuals\nwho contribute to the drive through\npurchase of the Easter seals or just\nby plain contributing.\nTwo camps are operated each year,\none near Micaville and Mount Mit\nchell for white crippled children, and\nthe other at Swansboro for Negro\nchildren. These camps are the follow\nthrough to treatment given the crip\npled child. The drive is about over,\nthe need is great. Send tue \u00bbciety\nin your county a contribution today,\nor mail it to \"Crippled Children\" in\ncare of the local Post Office.\nWHERE THE MOiVti \u03b9\nOld illusions die hard. A conspicu\nous example is the illusion thai uio\nrich pay most of the cost of \u03ba\u03c5\u03b1\u00b7;.,\u00b7\nment.\nAt one time there was much truth\nin this. But tiiat was in a vastly du\nierent age.\nborne tacts presented to a House\nCommittee by a spokesman for a\ngroup oi Khode Island industries tells\nthe sad tale. The individual income\ntax produces about one-hail' of alt\nfederal revenue. The oeginnuig r\nis 20 per cent, which applies to tue\nlowest taxable income. From there\nit climbs, lauuer-fashion, to a top\nyi per cent.\nAn uninformed person mig.it d.\nduce from this that the 20 per ceiu\nminimum tax is a comparatively un\nimportant re veil ue producer, lie\nco ildn't be more wrong for 84\nper cent of all income tax revenue\nis produced by that beginning rate.\nBy way of comparison, in a late yea\u00b7:\nthe rates above 50 per cent prouueed\nonly about one per cent of total fed\neral revenue.\nThe reason for this is simplf\nenough. There just aren't enough\nrich people to pay the tax bills, or\neven to make a sizeable dent in them.\nGovernment must get its money from\nwhere the money is and most of\nit is in the hands of people of small\nand moderate means. It is these peo\nple who have lhe greatest stake in\nefficient and economical government\n\u2014and in measures which would get\nrid of non-essential spending and re\nduce the tax load.\nA SERUM NELDILD\nit wouid be fine if scientific re\nsearch could turn up an anti-traffic\nvaccine. Where is the Dr. Salk of\ntraffic saiet\\ who will develop a\nserum to provide immunity from traf\nfic accidents.'\nWouldn't n be wonderful if chil\ndren couid be \\aecinated against\ndarting out from between parked\ncars; older pedestrians immunized\nagainst crossing between intersec\ntions; and motorists given a \"stop at\n\u03ce\u03a4\u039f\u0393 signs\" .-orum!\nSounds silly\u2014hut how can we wage\nwar on traffic accidents as we do on\ncancer, polio and other killing and\ncrippling diseases?\n\\A* \u03b9 \u03b9\nvauuvi. uanii: saieiy:\nTrue, there are traffic laws but\nthey prevent accidents only to the\nextent they are obeyed. Traffic en\ngineers and public officials are build\ning safety into ihe streets and high\nways. But how :ire we to build safety\ninto drivers and pedestrians?\nThe picture isn't completely black.\nTraffic safety experts are coming up\nwith answers, and the first step is to\ninvolve the public more and more in\ntraffic safety activities. Such a need\nwas recognized more than four year?,\nago with the organization of the\nGovernor's Traffic Safety Council. It\nis composed ui representatives of\ncivic, business and fraternal organi\nzations and of individual citizens who\ncarry the word to all groups in the\ncommunity.\nThe Governor's Traffic Safety\nCouncil's year-long program, \"Back\nthe Attack 011 Traffic Accidents\" has\nthese basic goals stepping up of\nall official traffic action, personal\nimprovement, as drivers and pedes\ntrians, support for official activities\nand building up of local satety coun\ncils in the.^e efforts to promote an\neii'ective and continuing traffic safety\nprogram with widesppread appeal.\nThese are the answers the vac\ncine needed to wipe out traffic acci\ndents. And they all involve you\u2014the\npublic. Drive and walk safely and\nobey all traffic laws! Support your\ntraffic officials! Work for a local\nsafety council!\nStatistics show that where these\nprograms are in operation, traffic\naccidents drop off. We have the vac\ncine. We can provide immunity by\nour behavior. All we need is the will!\nFree\nWheeling\nBY\u2014BILL CROWELL\nMIX UP\u00b7. Late in 1945 I\nwas living in North China and\nthere I saw the biggest traffic\nsnafu 1 ever hope to see. And\ncuriously enougn it all stem\nmed largely from what we\npreach so everlastingly hard in\nthis column motoring court\nesy and consideration.\nChiang Kai-shek's forces\nwere still in charge of North\nChina when th^ territory was\noccupied by th_\u00b7 !*irst Marine\nDivision, an ou'fit 1 called\nfor three weary years. Anyhow\nenroute to China the powers\nthat-be promulgated orders\nthat to conform >v\u00bb\u00bbh the cus\ntoms of the country all military\ntraffic would drive to the left,\na nioj-t commendable gesture\nwe all agreed.\ni suppose at th; i'nie Old One\nhad on hand sevcsal thousand\nassorted wheeled and tracked\nvehicles ranging Irom motor\ncycles to ten-wheeled tank re\ntrievers. To have this traffic,\nonce disembarked, iiu'vin,.\nsmoothly aiong the ancient\nstreets of IV-ipin:; was indeed\na stroke of planning genius. Or\nso it would seem.\nThe kicker e ime though a.\u00b7;\nthe first string el Jeeps timid\nly crept into the main thor\noughfare. bearing obediently to\nthe left side of the street. All\nwent well for hile, then a\nblast from a police whistle\nbrought the column up short.\nIn a torront c. pidgin Eng\nlish. the Chinese cop demanded\nto know \"what the dickens we\nwere doing.''\ni-aiunuy we started to ox\nplain, seizing on \u00ablit opportun\nity to show the Chinese we all\nwere obliging joes We wen\nguests; we AOUid drive as the\nChinese drive. So we thought.\nMeanwhile an uninterrupted\nstream of cars, trucks and\ntanks had begun to pour in\nfrom the anchored ships off\nTaku Bar. \\t the gates to the\ncity, drivers began swinging\ntheir vehicles to the left as\nordered. Traffic btgan to thick\nen up. Still we were stalled by\nthe outraged policeman who by\nnow had been joined by a\nnumber of t:is countrymen.\nThen several more carloads\nof Chinese Ligshots pulled up\n\u2014on the RIGHT side of the\navenue, mind you. entirely con\ntrary to the Chinese traffic\ncode.\nA couple of Chinese lumber\ntrucks appeared on the confus\ned scene\u2014also on the right.\nThen hundreds oi curious\ncoolies, tugging <\u00b71 rickshas,\njoined our growing number.\nThey packed the right side of\nthe now .-linked thoroughfare\neven tighter.\nFinally, like Zocco to the res\ncue, a Marine colonel made an\nentrance, bustling with auth\nority.\n\"What's all the Map?\" he de\nmanded. An ear shattering\nhorn down the line somewhere\nanswered him. He looked a\nround dazed.\nThe Chin .-so cops, meanwhile,\nhad gone into a huddle witb\nour division in\u00b7 *1 preter who\nat lirst, was as c fused as the\nrest of us. Suddenly a light\ndawned on 'lis fa.e, he smiled\nand a moment later laughed\naloud.\nThe Qolonel w.is incensed.\n\"And what's so confounded I\nfunny, Captain?\" he shot out.J\nThe colonel's patience was!\nshowing signs of wear.\n\"Well,\" began our language'\nman, \"t seems tnat before our'\narrival the Chinese govern-!\nment published an order re\ngarding traffic which I\n\"You don't mean ex\nploded the colonel.\n\"Yes sir. that's it Thr. \u0393\u00b7\u039a\u03af\u03b7_'\nII ese decided in honor of the A\n\u03b9 merican troops to direct all\n\u0397 traffic temporarily to the right\nI \u2014to conform with our way of\n1 driving.\"\nI SUDDEN THAWT It's\n\u0397 better to drive so that your\nlicense w*>l expire before you\ndo!\nIDIOCY Call me a fuss\nbudget if you \u00abvill, I'm still\nsaying baby shoes belong in;\nthe nursery not dangling\nfrom a rear viow mirror. A\nwestern state polk-c command-1\nsr found the problem of motor- j\nists addicted to hanging babyl\nshoes, dice and other trivia\nfrom their mirrors serious\nenough to gtt out a press re\nlease condemning the practice.\nNot to be outdone, our own\nhighway patrol chief, Col.\nJams\u00b7 R Smith claims the (ad\nIs \"not only silly but could eas\nily lead to an accident\"\nThe lawbooks say that no\nvehicle may be operated unless\nthe driver's vision through any\nrequired glass is normal. Or\nwords to that effect. Col.\nSmith, and m>i<ilf for that\nmatter, can Und no logical ex\nplanation for such idiocy.\nClear, normal visloo la a\nprime requisite for safe driv\ning. Anything that tends to ob\nscure it, however remotely, Is\nan inexcusable, dangerous\npractice. CoL Smith says the\nsame thing \u00abod he's been a po\nI 1 iceman 90 yean. I\nPLAIN\nTALK\nBY AL HAMM SON\n\"RECESSION\" TALK?\nFolks, including President Ike, are still talking\nabout the recession.\n1 can't get excited about the recession that w\u00ab\nare supposed to be experiencing\u00b7. Namely, because\n1 note with interest remodeling activity among lo\u00bb U\nmerchants and such things as addition of night\npositories as another Waccamaw Bank service to cus\ntomers in Chadbourn and Clarkton.\nIf people have money to invest in their belief\nthat the economic situation isn't depressing then 1\ncan still invest a little faith in that same belief.\nWANTED Harold Ward and I plan to attend t'\u00b7 u\nnational Jnycee convention in Los Angeles along\nabout June. Money is not a problem. The lack of it\nis. Have any money-making ideas you care to pa:\nalong? Phone me at 2*>21.\nNEW STORE The Army-Navy Store just open*')\nm Tabor City is another neat establishment wit;\ninerchandi.se that should appeal to the people. LittU\nby little, new stores continue to open and we soon\nwill have the wide variety offered by the larger tow\u00b7!-.\nThere is already very little you can't find right he\u00bb\u00b7\u00ab\u00b7\nin Tabor City.\nREMODELING C. C. Soles and Sons just completed\nremodeling the front of their dry goods store. It's\npretty and adds more to the already moderni^\ntouch applied to our business district in recent years.\nAnother remodeling job that makes a whale of a dif\nference in appearance on the business front is thai\ndone by W. S. Avant at the THRIFTY SHOP. Every\nlittle bit of improvement means that much more to\nTabor City.\nTHE TRUE TEST\nThe father is unable to work. The mother earns\n$12 per week. They have six children to feed and\nclothe. It would be a miserable world for some of us\nif we had to carry their burdens for just a few months\nVet, the youngsters never complain and the mother\nalways has a smile and pleasant word for each of\nher children. The abundance of love is quite evident.\nIt spells the difference between a rich family ami\none that is merely wealthy.\nAN OBSERVATION: Some people can't help beinjr\nstupid but they don't have to be so doggone proud\nof it! \u03b9\nSOBSERVATION AGAIN\u2014Some times a woman's\nwork is never done because she doesn't get started\nuntil 30 minutes before her husband gets home from\nwork.\nPITY THE TEACHERS\nIf you're wondering what a teacher has to put\nup with every day don't go to the school. Drop\nby the Tribune office \u03c5\u03b7 Wednesday afternoon aqii\ncheck the antics of the youngsters who sell papeiv-.\n\"Make him get out of my chair!\"\n\"I'm gonna' knock his block off!\"\n\"They saying bad words!\"\n\"When the papers gonna be ready?\"\n\"What's this for? How much it cost? Can 1\nhave it'.'\"\n\"When the papers gonna be ready?\"\n\"When the papers gonna be ready?\"\nThat's the gist of the comments you hear for what\nseems like days. Talking to them is like talking *t\nthe wind. Telling them to be quiet is like trying \u0393\u00bb\nget your own youngster quiet.\nAh, me. Pity the school teacher!\nCOMING ATTRACTION\nJobs are still plentiful despite talk of \"recession\"\nand \"depression\".\nYou'll enjoy a coming bit of personal experien\u00b7\"'\nthat brought about this conclusion.\nIt's too early to give details about the survey but\nthe data continues to dribble in.\nPLACE ORDERS EARLY\n\u2014FOR\u2014\nEASTER FLOWERS\nPotted Plants\nCorsages\nCemetery Arrangements\nTABOR CITY FLORIST\n\"We Telegraph Floivers Anywhere\"\nMAUDE STEPHENS HUFHAivl. Owner\n206 E. Fifth St. Tabor City\n(Next Door to Inman Funeral Home)\nDay Phone 2011 Nijiht Phone 21 !\u00bb4\n\u0397. \u0392. TODD\nLHe Insurance\n\"For Life Ineurance Service At Its Best\"\nP. O. Box 408 Phon\u00ab 4211\nTabor City, N. C.\n\"Tabor City\u2014\u039b Town With A Ctty future*\nPlll,,kl1 *T\u00abnr W\u00bb<wii| la Mhr CttrTi^Qm\u00abi\u00b7\n\u03b7\u00b7 ammmi\u00b7 mm\u00ab \u03bf*.\nW. BOIAO\u00b7 CAB